CONTENT: o ocean protocol facilita a troca de dados usando um protocolo descentralizado que combina nfts de dados  datatokens e tecnologia compute-to-data (c2d). os provedores de dados podem publicar seus serviÃ§os de dados como erc721 data nfts e erc20 datatokens  que permitem o controle de acesso descentralizado por meio de token-gating. para acessar um conjunto de dados ou serviÃ§o de dados  Ã© preciso ter os datatokens correspondentes. o consumo de serviÃ§os de dados envolve o gasto de datatokens. o compute-to-data permite a compra e a venda de dados privados  preservando a privacidade. ele permite que os cÃ¡lculos sejam executados nos dados sem que eles saiam de suas instalaÃ§Ãµes  garantindo que somente os resultados sejam visÃ­veis para o consumidor. o ocean market Ã© um exemplo de um mercado de dados descentralizado em que compradores e vendedores podem trocar dados e algoritmos  com ferramentas para publicar e monetizar a propriedade intelectual usando a tecnologia blockchain.

AUTHOR: semanticbeeng
CONTENT: hello - my name is nick vintila  and am focused on building support for `machine learning engineering`  to bridge the gap from experimental analyses and data products   between science and engineering. (as architect often need to puzzle together tech with duplicate functionality and conflicting designs)  in particular am working on a `feature registry` & `feature store` using `apache hudi`. if you like any of the ideas here https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/hudi/hudi+for+continuous+deep+analytics then would love to discuss.  some topics that i am working from: hoping that these hash tags make it easier to find affinities and search.  `#datagovernance` https://twitter.com/search?q=%23datagovernance%20(from%3asemanticbeeng)&src=typed_query `#machinelearningengineering`  https://twitter.com/search?q=%23machinelearningengineering%20(from%3asemanticbeeng) `#datafabric` https://gist.github.com/semanticbeeng/2edad7a5e2cd7cd6af5cde824b4e0da0 `#nonstationarylearning`   * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23nonstationarylearning%20(from%3asemanticbeeng)   * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23conceptdrift%20(from%3asemanticbeeng)   * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23covariateshift%20(from%3asemanticbeeng)  not a `blockchain` expert but am working on techniques to bridge between distributed application logic and `smart contract` functionality.  i studied `oceanprotocol` vision and high level design material quite a bit but not yet knowledgeable enough. if you think am missing some point please point me to material that i need to study.  based on my understanding so far i do have some premises on how my work & focus relate to `oceanprotocol`.  one of my first goals is to verify those premises with people here and their experiences.  here's the first one https://twitter.com/semanticbeeng/status/1319889341074804736 > *"data" needs to be a #datagovernance "asset" before being a #blockchain "asset" because one cannot contract and trade in terms unless they are well specified.*

AUTHOR: hebbianloop
CONTENT: hi  i just realized i never introduced myself! i'm shady  a phd in neuroscience and founder of opscientia. my efforts have been dedicated to building a de-sci (decentralized science) utilizing all of the benefits of web 3.0 to accelerate the pace of scientific innovation through peer-to-peer storage of massive datasets  confidential cloud computing  and sharing through data marketplaces. our mission is to help transform the process of scientific discovery to include citizen scientists working together in parallel with traditional academia.

AUTHOR: mantisclone
CONTENT: i want to expand upon my initial introduction:  my name is david hunt-mateo and i'm a software engineer with 7 years of professional experience. for the last three years  i developed a cross-platform  on-device  noise-robust speech recognition library. users liked it because it would work on whatever hardware they had  it never transmitted their audio to the cloud  and it would work in harsh environments like the middle of the ocean or a noise manufacturing floor. unfortunately  i was laid off at the end of 2020. soon after  i began reading about blockchain and was immediately enthralled by the benefits that decentralized web 3 technologies could bring. i am currently participating in the kernel block 2 fellowship program hosted by gitcoin.   i've spent 4 weeks researching to understand the web 3 landscape and to determine exactly what use cases excited me most. i determined that i am most passionate about the user's right to privacy and data ownership  especially regarding ai and communication. having developed a production ai system myself  i'm familiar with the massive amounts of data required as well as the difficulties small companies face when trying to acquire data. furthermore  it's not hard to recognize the tactics that larger companies employ to extract data from their users. i think the ocean protocol could provide a solution to these problems  and furthermore  that it is poised for massive growth as the mainstream consciousness becomes aware of the abuse it's suffered at the hands of big tech.   as such  the ocean protocol tops the list of projects i'd like to become involved with. my career has meandered through several industries and many layers of the technology stack. i consider myself a jack of many trades  adept at learning/applying new technologies  and a skilled communicator. my specialties in the past have been cross-platform development  desktop and native android apps  and embedded software.

AUTHOR: ssskylark
CONTENT: what sets ocean apart is  simply allows data sales without losing control over the ip on the data - this is especially useful for machine learning/ai tasks. the algorithms can train a model on data without the data leaving the owners premesis. this enables data usage that was not possible before e.g. for medical data.  additionally it also enables the creation of datatokens and liquidity pools for datasets which allow for price discovery  curation and reputation of datasets. high quality datasets will have different setups of their datatokens than unsuccessful ones.

CONTENT: hello everyone! thanks @sheridan | ocean protocol for giving me an intro. my name is mats brodÃ©n based in stockholm  sweden. i'm the curator for a multi-stakeholder ecosystem called sense nation. we are exploring the interface between nanotech and dlt together with onboarded companies that drive demand. we want to reach out to the ocean community in order to expand our imagination capacity when it comes to dlt and nanotech. in a way we blur the line between the physical and the digital. we are building or rather measuring out a hidden asset layers in matter. looking forward to connect to you. i'm happy to give you an intro on what we are doing. all the best mats@embeddednano.com

CONTENT: hi robin  thanks for your questions. well we will focus on nano sensors that "dig" up unique data. it is kind of dynamic identities that will make it possible  via ai  to ask material systems like machines and organisms how they are doing. an ontology of a thing.  initially we will focus on machines and predictive maintenance. it will be possible to do what you ask but as a first step it will as feedback loop. i'm curios to ask you how we can develop this into something that can address for instance the oracle problem. feed smart contract with data.

AUTHOR: stippes
CONTENT: hey guys! looking forward to learn more about the ocean protocol. i am working for a research institute in the netherlands and we are looking at the blockchain to save our participant data in an open and transparent manner (although it is a pretty early stage pilot project) do you know whom i could talk to that is familiar with the use of psychometric data on the blockchain?  or any pointers towards good learning material are also welcome.

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: you should try https://oceanacademy.io - this gives a good introduction to ocean protocol. in ocean protocol the data is not stored on the blockchain but the governance is organised via the blockchain. so the data resides on premise and the access to the data by algorithms is organised via compute-to-data. this means that the data is not going to leave the data storage and that the data owner (you) can allow algorithms to access the data or not.

AUTHOR: rikrapmund
CONTENT: hi everyone! my name is rik rapmund  supporter of ocean since the ico and founder of workpi: an hr tech startup that predicts the required skills for rapidly evolving jobs in organisations to reduce skill gaps and eliminate mismatches. besides workpi we are also building work x: a decentralized platform economy for work where service providers and customers can work together without intermediaries.   because we believe that the personal data of our users should be owned and controlled by themselves  we are working together with the european commission on a self-sovereign identity solution (ssi). users will be able to connect their career related data such as assessments  diplomas  certificates or references to their digital passport/identity. this is also where ocean comes along. it's a great thing to give data back to the people  but is also comes with a challenge: how do we learn from it when the data is scattered around the world? the technology of ocean is very promising to solve this problem. to this end we introduce *compute-to-ssi*. learn more about our proposal here: https://port.oceanprotocol.com/t/workpi-oceandao-round-9/862  we're very interested to get to know the community and hear your feedback!   cheers!   rik

CONTENT: hey!  we're glad to see you here in the ocean protocol communityðŸ˜ŽðŸŒŠ  to start learning about ocean protocol and its role in creating a decentralized data marketplace  you can follow these steps:  understand ocean protocol's mission and core technologies: ocean protocol aims to level the playing field for ai and data by enabling the monetization of ai models and data while preserving privacy. its core technologies include data nfts & datatokens for token-gated access control and compute-to-data for buying and selling private data while preserving privacy.  explore what you can do with ocean: depending on your interest or expertise  you can engage with ocean protocol in various capacities such as a builder  data scientist  or ocean holder. each role offers different opportunities  from building token-gated ai dapps and apis to earning rewards through data farming.  join the ocean protocol community: becoming an ocean ambassador is a great way to get involved. you can join ocean protocol's discord server  participate in discussions  and apply to become an ambassador through the #treasure-hunter channel on discord.  learn through doing: consider participating in data challenges hosted by ocean protocol to apply your skills in real-world problems and earn prizes.  dive deeper into documentation: visit the developers and data scientists pages on ocean protocol's website for step-by-step instructions  apis  libraries  and other tools to build dapps or integrate with the ocean ecosystem.  stay informed: keep up with the latest updates and resources by following ocean protocol's official channels and participating in community events.  https://oceanprotocol.com/  https://market.oceanprotocol.com/

AUTHOR: sheridan_oceanprotocol
CONTENT: @oceangpt can your explain the difference between datatokens and datanfts as well as provide details as to what they are used for and why.

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: sure  i'd be happy to explain the difference between datatokens and data nfts in ocean protocol.  data nfts are non-fungible tokens that represent a unique piece of data  such as a dataset or a data service. each data nft is unique and can be owned by a single entity at a time. data nfts can be traded on data marketplaces  allowing data providers to monetize their data assets.  datatokens  on the other hand  are erc20 tokens that represent a fractional ownership of a data nft. they allow for the creation of a market for data  where data providers can sell fractional ownership of their data assets to multiple buyers. datatokens can be traded on decentralized exchanges and used in defi applications.  in summary  data nfts represent unique pieces of data  while datatokens represent fractional ownership of those data nfts. together  they enable the creation of data markets and the monetization of data assets.

CONTENT: @oceangpt can you help me with a coding problem i have? i want to make it possible to enter parameters in the ocean protocol marketplace and pass them to a compute-to-data job. can you give me an example on how to implement that?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: sure  i can help you with that. one way to implement this is to create a form on the marketplace where users can input the parameters they want to pass to the compute-to-data job. then  when the user submits the form  the marketplace can use the ocean protocol api to create a new compute-to-data job and pass the parameters as input to the job. here's some sample code to get you started:  ``` // define the parameters that the user can input const parameters = {   param1: ''    param2: ''    param3: '' };  // create a form to collect the user's input const form = document.createelement('form'); form.addeventlistener('submit'  async (event) => {   event.preventdefault();      // get the user's input from the form   const input1 = event.target.elements.param1.value;   const input2 = event.target.elements.param2.value;   const input3 = event.target.elements.param3.value;      // create a new compute-to-data job using the ocean protocol api   const jobid = await ocean.compute.createcomputejob({     input: {       param1: input1        param2: input2        param3: input3     }   });      // redirect the user to the job details page   window.location.href = `/jobs/${jobid}`; });  // add input fields to the form for each parameter for (const [key  value] of object.entries(parameters)) {   const input = document.createelement('input');   input.type = 'text';   input.name = key;   input.placeholder = key;   form.appendchild(input); }  // add the form to the marketplace page document.body.appendchild(form); ```  this code creates a form with input fields for each parameter  and listens for the form to be submitted. when the form is submitted  it uses the ocean protocol api to create a new compute-to-data job with the user's input as the job input. finally  it redirects the user to the job details page so they can monitor the job's progress.

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: @oceangpt how can i create a fixed rate exchange in ocean.py?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: to create a fixed rate exchange in ocean.py  you can use the `create_fixed_rate_exchange` function from the `ocean.py` library. here's an example code snippet:  ```python from ocean_lib.config import config from ocean_lib.ocean import util from ocean_lib.ocean.util import from_base_18 from ocean_lib.web3_internal.wallet import wallet from ocean_lib.models.data_token import datatoken from ocean_lib.models.fixed_rate_exchange import fixedrateexchange  # set up configuration and wallet config = config('config.ini') wallet = wallet(config.parity_address  config.parity_password)  # set up data token and exchange parameters dt = datatoken(config  config.metadata_store_url  wallet) dt_name = 'my data token' dt_symbol = 'mdt' dt_total_supply = 1000 exchange_rate = from_base_18(1)  # 1 ocean = 1 mdt  # create data token and mint initial supply dt.create(dt_name  dt_symbol  dt_total_supply  from_wallet=wallet) dt.mint(wallet.address  dt_total_supply)  # create fixed rate exchange exchange = fixedrateexchange.create(     config      wallet      dt      exchange_rate      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply      dt_total_supply )  # print exchange information print(f"exchange id: {exchange.exchange_id}") print(f"exchange contract address: {exchange.contract_address}") ```  this code creates a new data token  mints some initial supply  and then creates a new fixed rate exchange for that token with a 1:1 exchange rate with ocean. you can adjust the exchange rate and other parameters as needed for your use case.

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: @oceangpt how can i change the price on a fixed rate exchange?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: to change the price on a fixed rate exchange  you need to update the exchange rate parameter in the contract. this can be done by calling the `setexchangerate` function on the fixed rate exchange contract  passing in the new exchange rate as a parameter.  here's an example code snippet using `web3.js`:  ```javascript const web3 = require('web3'); const web3 = new web3('http://localhost:8545');  const exchangecontractaddress = '0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890'; const exchangecontractabi = [...]; // abi for the fixed rate exchange contract  const exchangecontract = new web3.eth.contract(exchangecontractabi  exchangecontractaddress);  const newexchangerate = web3.utils.towei('0.5'  'ether'); // new exchange rate of 1 mdt = 0.5 ocean  // call the setexchangerate function on the contract exchangecontract.methods.setexchangerate(newexchangerate).send({ from: '0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890' })   .then((receipt) => {     console.log('exchange rate updated successfully:'  receipt);   })   .catch((error) => {     console.error('error updating exchange rate:'  error);   }); ```  note that you need to have the appropriate permissions to call this function on the contract  and you should also ensure that the new exchange rate is reasonable and reflects the current market conditions.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt how exactly does ocean protocol token-gating work?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: in ocean protocol  token-gating refers to the process of requiring a certain amount of tokens to access or use a particular data asset. this is done through the use of datatokens  which are erc20 tokens that represent a specific data asset. the owner of the data asset can set a certain amount of datatokens as the access fee for the asset  and users must hold that amount of tokens in their wallet in order to access the data. this creates a market for the data asset  as users must purchase the necessary tokens in order to access the data. token-gating can also be used to incentivize data providers to share their data  as they can set a higher access fee for their more valuable data assets.

CONTENT: @oceangpt explain in detail what information is held in a data nft and what information is held in a datatoken

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: a data nft (erc721) represents a unique data asset and contains metadata such as the asset's name  description  and creator. it also includes a reference to the asset's did (decentralized identifier) and ddo (decentralized data object) which contain additional information about the asset such as its location and access control policies.  on the other hand  a datatoken (erc20) is used to access data services and represents a certain amount of access to a specific data asset. it contains information such as the amount of access it provides and the address of the data provider.  during the purchase flow  aquarius is used to store and retrieve metadata about the data asset  while provider is used to manage access control and provide access to the data asset. datatokens are used to transfer access to the data asset from the buyer to the data provider.  aquarius stores metadata off-chain and can be run locally or remotely. running aquarius locally allows for more control over the metadata and faster access to it  while pointing to a remote instance allows for easier maintenance and scalability.  the advantage of running aquarius yourself instead of using the rest api is that you have more control over the metadata and can customize it to your specific needs. it also allows for faster access to the metadata and reduces reliance on external services.  it is possible to utilize ocean protocol without using aquarius  but it would require manually managing metadata and access control policies  which can be time-consuming and error-prone. aquarius provides a convenient and standardized way to manage metadata and access control for data assets.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt can anyone access an assets access control information on aquarius or is that information encrypted?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: identify instance of aquarius to provider  when decrypting assets. provider may allow or deny decryption based on this address. this means that the access control information for an asset on aquarius is encrypted and can only be accessed by the provider who holds the private key for that specific instance of aquarius.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: provider is a component of the ocean protocol stack that provides rest api for data services. it is responsible for accessing and providing data assets  performing checks on chain for buyer permissions and payments  encrypting the url and metadata during publish  decrypting the url when the dataset is downloaded or a compute job is started  providing access to data assets by streaming data  and providing compute services. provider is typically run by the data provider. to run your own provider  you can clone the repo and understand the config parameters  envvars vs files  and learn about off-chain services such as ocean provider for data services and aquarius metadata store.

CONTENT: sure  here are the steps to run your own provider:  1. clone the provider repository: ```bash git clone git@github.com:oceanprotocol/provider.git cd provider/ ```  2. initialize the off-chain services (aquarius and provider) by cloning the barge repository and running it: ```bash git clone https://github.com/oceanprotocol/barge.git cd barge/ ./start_ocean.sh --with-provider2 --no-dashboard ```  3. set up the environment variables in your `.env` file: ``` flask_app=ocean_provider/run.py provider_address=your ethereum address goes here provider_private_key= the private key or string containing a dict of chain_id to private key pairs provider_fee_token = the address of erc20 token used to get fees  or string containing a dict of chain_id to token address pairs ```  4. start the provider server by running: ```bash flask run --port=8030 ```  5. refer to the api.md file for endpoints and payloads.  that's it! you now have your own provider up and running.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt explain in detail the metadatacreated and metadataupdated events

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: sure  i can explain the metadatacreated and metadataupdated events in detail.  the metadatacreated event is triggered when metadata for an asset is first published on-chain. the metadata is first compressed (using lzma) and encrypted  and then published on-chain. the metadata on-chain is not kept in storage  but rather is captured in an event log named metadatacreated. this event contains information such as the address of the publisher  the metadata hash  and the block number.  the metadataupdated event  on the other hand  is triggered when metadata for an asset is updated. this event contains information such as the address of the entity that updated the metadata  the state of the asset  the decryptor url  the flags  the data  the metadata hash  the timestamp  and the block number.  both events are important for tracking changes to the metadata of an asset on the ocean protocol network.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt can you give an example of what information would be included in a metadatacreated event

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: sure  here's an example of what information would be included in a metadatacreated event:  {   "event": "metadatacreated"    "returnvalues": {     "did": "did:op:123456789abcdefghi"      "owner": "0x123456789abcdef"      "metadata": "0xabcdef123456789"      "timestamp": "2023-03-28t17:39:46z"   }    "blocknumber": 123456    "transactionhash": "0x123456789abcdef"    "transactionindex": 0    "blockhash": "0xabcdef123456789"    "logindex": 0    "removed": false }  in this example  the metadatacreated event includes the did (decentralized identifier) of the asset  the ethereum address of the owner  the encrypted and compressed metadata  and the timestamp of when the event was created. other information such as the block number  transaction hash  and log index are also included for reference.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt can you give an example of the metadata information that is encrypted and compressed during a metadatacreated event

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: during a metadatacreated event  the metadata information that is encrypted and compressed can include various attributes such as the asset name  description  author  license  and other relevant information about the asset. for example  if the asset is a dataset  the metadata can include information about the data format  size  and schema. all of this information is compressed and encrypted to ensure privacy and security when published on-chain.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt how does the provider check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: the provider checks whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking the access control list (acl) stored on the blockchain. the acl specifies which ethereum addresses have permission to access the metadata. when a user requests access to the metadata  the provider checks the user's ethereum address against the acl to determine whether the user has permission to access the metadata. if the user has permission  the provider decrypts and decompresses the metadata and returns it to the user. if the user does not have permission  the provider denies the request and does not provide access to the metadata.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt is there a difference between a wallet having permission to view metadata information of an asset and having permission to access the data asset itself?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: yes  there is a difference. having permission to view metadata information of an asset means that the wallet can see the information about the asset  such as its name  description  and creator  but cannot access the actual data asset itself. on the other hand  having permission to access the data asset means that the wallet can retrieve and use the actual data asset. the provider can check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking the access control list (acl) associated with the asset's did. the acl specifies which ethereum addresses have permission to view the metadata information and/or access the data asset.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt how can a publisher implement fine-grained access controls to determine who can view the metadata information

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: one way a publisher can implement fine-grained access controls to determine who can view the metadata information is by restricting metadata caching to publishers in a specific list of publisher addresses. this list  called allowed_publishers  would contain the addresses of publishers who are authorized to view the metadata information. the metadata itself is first compressed and encrypted before being published on-chain  and is captured in an event log named metadatacreated. the aquarius service defers to the provider for encryption and decryption  and supports utf-8 encoded strings. the provider can check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking if the wallet's address is included in the allowed_publishers list. there is a difference between a wallet having permission to view metadata information of an asset and having permission to access the data asset itself. access to the data asset itself would require additional permissions and authentication.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt is the metadata information that is kept inside of aquarius a copy of the metadata information encrypted and stored on-chain?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: no  the metadata information kept inside of aquarius is not a copy of the metadata information encrypted and stored on-chain. instead  aquarius caches the metadata information that is published on-chain and stores it in an elasticsearch database. the metadata is first compressed and encrypted before being published on-chain  and aquarius defers to the provider for encryption and decryption.

AUTHOR: christian_casazza
CONTENT: @oceangpt what is the difference between caching the metadata information and copying the metadata information?

AUTHOR: OceanGPT#0740
CONTENT: caching the metadata information involves storing a copy of the metadata on a separate system  such as elasticsearch  for faster search and retrieval. copying the metadata information refers to publishing the metadata on-chain  which is the initial step in the process of creating a new asset. so  caching is a performance optimization technique  while copying is a necessary step in the asset creation process.

CONTENT: a motion to demurrer is a legal motion made by a defendant in response to a complaint filed by a plaintiff. the motion argues that even if all the allegations in the complaint are true  they do not constitute a legal claim or cause of action. in other words  the defendant is saying that the plaintiff has failed to state a claim upon which relief can be granted. the purpose of a demurrer is to challenge the legal sufficiency of the complaint and to ask the court to dismiss the case. if the court grants the demurrer  the plaintiff may be given an opportunity to amend the complaint to address the deficiencies identified by the defendant.

CONTENT: to create a dispenser from a datatoken using ocean.js  you need to follow these steps:  1. first  you need to initialize ocean and get the account. here is an example:  ```javascript import { ocean  confighelper } from '@oceanprotocol/lib'  const config = new confighelper().getconfig('rinkeby') const ocean = await ocean.getinstance(config)  // accounts const account = (await ocean.accounts.list())[0] ```  2. then  you need to create a new datatoken:  ```javascript const datatoken = await ocean.datatokens.create('https://example.com'  account) ```  3. after that  you can create a dispenser:  ```javascript const dispenseraddress = await ocean.dispenser.createdispenser(datatoken  account) ```  4. finally  you can approve and request datatokens:  ```javascript await ocean.dispenser.approve(datatoken  100  account) await ocean.dispenser.requesttokens(datatoken  100  account) ```  please note that you need to replace `'https://example.com'` with your own url  and `100` with the amount of datatokens you want to approve and request. also  make sure that the account you are using has enough balance to create and request datatokens.
